nd `t ∈ [0, 1]`, we have `a^t * b^(1-t) ≤ t*a + (1-t)*b`. \n\nSetting `t = 1/p`, `a = |f i|^p`, `b = |g i|^q`. Then `t*a = |f i|^p * (1/p)`. `(1-t)*b = |g i|^q * (1 - 1/p) = |g i|^q * (q/p)`. \n\nSo `|f i|^p * (1/p) + |g i|^q * (q/p) ≥ |f i|^p * |g i|^q`. \n\nBut we need `|f i|^p * |g i|^q ≥ |f i * g i|`. \n\nWait, this is not the right approach. Let's think about weighted AM-GM on `|f i|^p` and `|g i|^q`.\n\nLet's apply weighted AM-GM on the terms `|f i|^p` and `|g i|^q` with weights `1/p` and `1/q` respectively. Since `1/p + 1/q = 1`, we get:\n`|f i|^p * (1/p) + |g i|^q * (1/q) ≥ (|f i|^p)^(1/p) * (|g i|^q)^(1/q)`\n\nThe right side simplifies to `|f i| * |g i|`. The left side is `(1/p) * |f i|^p + (1/q) * |g i|^q`. \n\nSo we get `(1/p) * |f i|^p + (1/q) * |g i|^q ≥ |f i| * |g i|`. \n\nThis is exactly the inequality we need! Multiplying through by `p*q`, we get `q * |f i|^p + p * |g i|^q ≥ p*q * |f i| * |g i|`. \n\nBut we need `|f i|^p * |g i|^q ≥ |f i * g i|`. \n\nWait, this is not the same inequality. We need `|f i|^p * |g i|^q ≥ |f i * g i|`. \n\nLet's think again. Let's apply weighted AM-GM on `|f i|` and `|g i|` with weights `p` and `q` respectively. Since `p + q` is not necessarily 1, this is not directly applicable.\n\nWait, the weighted AM-GM inequality states that for `a, b ≥ 0` and `t, s ≥ 0` with `t + s = 1`, we have `a^t * b^s ≤ t*a + s*b`. \n\nLet's set `a = |f i|`, `b = |g i|`, `t = 1/p`, `s = 1/q`. Since `1/p + 1/q = 1`, we have:\n`|f i|^(1/p) * |g i|^(1/q) ≤ (1/p)*|f i| + (1/q)*|g i|`\n\nRaising both sides to the power of `p*q`:\n`(|f i|^(1/p) * |g i|^(1/q))^(p*q) ≤ ((1/p)*|f i| + (1/q)*|g i|)^(p*q)`\n`|f i|^q * |g i|^p ≤ ( (q/p)*|f i|^p + (p/q)*|g i|^q )^(p*q)`\n\nWait, this is getting too complicated. Let's think of a different approach.\n\nAlternatively, we can use the weighted AM-GM inequality on `|f i|^p` and `|g i|^q` with weights `1/p` and `1/q`.\n\nLet's apply weighted AM-GM on `|f i|^p` and `|g i|^q` with weights `1/p` and `1/q`:\n`|f i|^p * (1/p) + |g i|^q * (1/q) ≥ (|f i|^p)^(1/p) * (|g i|^q)^(1/q)`\n`|f i|^p * (1/p) + |g i|^q * (1/q) ≥ |f i| * |g i|`\n\nThis is exactly the inequality we need! So we can apply weighted AM-GM to get:\n`|f i|^p * (1/p) + |g i|^q * (1/q) ≥ |f i| * |g i|`\n\nSumming over all `i`, we get:\n`(1/p) * ∑ |f i|^p + (1/q) * ∑ |g i|^q ≥ ∑ |f i * g i|`\n\nMultiplying through by `p*q`:\n`q * ∑ |f i|^p + p * ∑ |g i|^q ≥ p*q * ∑ |f i * g i|`\n\nBut we need `∑ |f i * g i| ≤ (∑ |f i|^p)^(1/p) * (∑ |g i|^q)^(1/q)`. \n\nThis inequality is a direct application of Hölder's inequality for sequences. In Lean, we can prove this using properties of conjugate exponents and the weighted AM-GM inequality.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\n            have h8 : |f i| ^ p * |g i| ^ q ≥ |f i * g i| := by\n              have h9 : |f i * g i| = |f i| * |g i| := by\n                simp [abs_mul]\n              rw [h9]\n              have h10 : |f i| ^ p * |g i| ^ q ≥ |f i| * |g i| := by\n                have h11 : |f i| ≥ 0 := by apply abs_nonneg\n                have h12 : |g i| ≥ 0 := by apply abs_nonneg\n                have h13 : |f i| ^ p * |g i| ^ q ≥ |f i| * |g i| := by\n                  have h14 : |f i| ^ p ≥ |f i| := by\n                    have h15 : |f i| ≥ 0 := by apply abs_nonneg\n                    have h16 : |f i| ^ p ≥ |f i| ^ 1 := by\n                      apply pow_le_pow_left\n                      all_goals linarith [show (1 : ℝ) ≤ p by linarith [show 1 ≤ p by simpa using p.isConj1]]\n                    have h17 : |f i| ^ 1 = |f i| := by\n                      simp\n                    linarith [h16, h17]\n```\n\nWait, this is getting very involved. Let's think about a more direct proof. We need to show that `|f i|^p * |g i|^q ≥ |f i * g i|`. This is equivalent to `|f i|^p * |g i|^q ≥ |f i| * |g i|`.\n\nSince `1/p + 1/q = 1`, we can use the weighted AM-GM inequality. Let's set `x = |f i|^p` and `y = |g i|^q`. Then we need to prove `x^(1/p) * y^(1/q) ≤ (1/p)x + (1/q)y`